The `<Switch>` component used in React routing is specifically provided by the React Router library.

To use `<Switch>`, you need to import it from React Router. Here's an example import statement:

```javascript
import { Switch } from 'react-router-dom';
```

The `react-router-dom` package is the version of React Router that is used for web applications, so make sure you have it installed in your project by running:

```
npm install react-router-dom
```

Once you have `react-router-dom` installed and imported, you can use `<Switch>` to render only the first `<Route>` or `<Redirect>` that matches the current location.

Here's an example of how you can use `<Switch>` in your router configuration:

```jsx
import { BrowserRouter as Router, Route, Switch } from 'react-router-dom';

// ...

const App = () => {
  return (
    <Router>
      <Switch>
        <Route exact path="/" component={Home} />
        <Route path="/about" component={About} />
        <Route path="/contact" component={Contact} />
        <Route component={NotFound} />
      </Switch>
    </Router>
  );
};
```

In the example above, `<Switch>` is used to render either the `Home`, `About`, or `Contact` component based on the current URL path. If none of these paths match, the `NotFound` component will be rendered.

Note that `<Switch>` ensures that only the first matching component is rendered, which is why the not-found route component is placed at the bottom, as it will match any unmatched paths.
